  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison sends the &quot;Call for a Convention to oppose penal legislation in regard to the observance of a Sabath day, and to explode the mischievous delusion, that one day in a week is more holy than another.&quot; Garrison requests for authorization to add Samuel Joseph May&apos;s name to the list of people supporting the &quot;Call for a Convention&quot; letter. Garrison includes a list of people who have already signed the circular letter. Garrison comments to Samuel J. May: &quot;I trust you will be pleased with this protest against legislative tyranny over conscience---this vindication of the real nature and spirit of Christianity.&quot; Garrison&apos;s health has improved, but he is not as well as before his illness.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On the verso of this handwritten letter by William Lloyd Garrison, is the &quot;Anti-Sabbath Convention&quot; circular letter &quot;to the friends of civil and religious liberty.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
